vel it definitely does not work. They are the target for all the nasty small minded thugs. Alot of the bullying is very subtle - for example - sitting close to and watching a boy with Aspergers while he works at the computer until he cracks and shouts at them. &#10;There is the so called &quot;alternative curriculum&quot; for the less able, this takes all the vulnerable kids and lumps them in with the yob element. The teacher can't control them and bullying is rife. There seems to be a game of &quot;make him lose his temper&quot; picking on the ADHD kids until they start shouting and hit out. &#10;We have two &quot;special&quot; schools here and they are both fantastic, the kids seem to thrive there, taking part in all sorts of activities, sporting and academic. They even set up their own small business through the Young Entrepreneurs scheme last year. Can't see any of them being included in that in a mainstream High School. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1204" language="en" documentId="4912" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="Jo M(16)" date="02-04-10 20:19" docType="forumpost" origUrl="http://www.netmums.com/coffeehouse/general-coffeehouse-chat-514/news-current-affairs-topical-discussion-12/405944-special-needs-children-mainstream-schools-all.html" topic="mainstreaming" thumbsUp="0" thumbsDown="0" origId="4912" notes="" title="Special Needs children in Mainstream Schools"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="277"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="278" end="564"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="47" sofa="1" begin="565" end="879"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="51" sofa="1" begin="880" end="1204"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43 47 51"/></xmi:XMI>